\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/cmf.twist}{Twist}}
\begin{definition}\label{cmf.twist}
\uses{character.dirichlet,character.dirichlet.conductor,character.dirichlet.galois_orbit,character.dirichlet.primitive,cmf.galois_conjugate,cmf.galois_orbit,cmf.inner_twist,cmf.newform}
Associated to each \hyperref[cmf.newform]{newform} $f$ and \hyperref[character.dirichlet.primitive]{primitive} \hyperref[character.dirichlet]{Dirichlet character} $\psi$, there is a unique newform $g:=f\otimes\psi$, the \textbf{twist} of $f$ by $\psi$, that satisfies
\[
a_n(g)=\psi(n)a_n(f)
\]
for all integers $n\ge 1$ coprime to $N$ and the \hyperref[character.dirichlet.conductor]{conductor} of $\psi$.  The newforms $f$ and $g$ are then \textbf{twist equivalent}.  When $g$ is a \hyperref[cmf.galois_conjugate]{Galois conjugate} of $f$, it is said to be an \hyperref[cmf.inner_twist]{inner twist}.

The \hyperref[cmf.galois_orbit]{newform orbit} $[g]$ is a \textbf{twist} of the newform orbit $[f]$ by the \hyperref[character.dirichlet.galois_orbit]{character orbit} $[\psi]$ if some $g\in [g]$ is a twist of $f$ by some $\psi$ in $[\psi]$.  This may occur with \hyperref[cmf.twist_multiplicity]{multiplicity}.

Twist equivalence is an equivalence relation.  The \textbf{twist class} of a newform or newform orbit is its equivalence class under this relation.

In the LMFDB each twist class is identified by the label of its \hyperref[cmf.minimal_twist]{minimal twist}.
\end{definition}
